The below datasets contain aggregated London Ambulance Service dispatch&nbsp;data separated out by the type of incident called out to.&nbsp;
Source data received by SafeStats consists of a raw dataset that contains records for every ambulance vehicle dispatched. The data is a snapshot at a point in time, and due to potential retrospective actions may not be a&nbsp;representation of the actual event. However the data is relevant for understanding broad patterns in different types of crime and disorder nonetheless.
Utilsiing groups of callout codes agreed with the LAS, useful subsets of the data have been provided relating to dispatches to different types of incidents.&nbsp;
Subsets provided (as well as 'all dispatches') include those that are alcohol-related, assaults (subsets for female and teen victims, and alcohol-related), weapon injuries (subsets for knife and gun injuries), animal-related injuries, and cocaine/heroin overdoses.&nbsp;
These are available in the 'Dispatches' files below.&nbsp;
By deduplicating the dispatch records, it is possible to create subsets of incident counts in the same categories above (ie. 6 ambulance dispatches to 1 incident of knife injury).
These are available in the 'Incidents' files below.
However the subjective and often retrospective nature of recording of the various dispatch fields by multiple LAS attendees means that these can vary between dispatched vehicles. Therefore by using only the incident details of the first dispatched vehicle an element of potential error is introduced into the deduplicated subsets. Please bear this in mind when considering the data.&nbsp;
The data covers from Jan-2010 to the most recent data that is available, updated monthly, and available at borough and ward geographies. Should you wish to obtain data prior to 2010, please use the contact details below.&nbsp;
Data are available in both tabbed (xlsx) format, split out by each subset above, and raw machine-readable (csv) format

The files below provide the affordable housing statistics for GLA funded programmes. The GLA is committed to open and transparent reporting and will publish statistics relating to housing delivery in London.
This information supplements previous releases of national housing statistics published by the Homes and Communities Agency (external website).
